{"title_page": "The Berenstain Bears (2003 TV series)", "text_new": "{{distinguish|The Berenstain Bears (1985 TV series)}}\n{{more citations needed|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox television\n|show_name          = The Berenstain Bears\n|image              =\n|caption            =\n|camera             = \n|picture_format     = [[480i]] ([[Standard-definition television|SDTV]])\n|audio_format       = [[Stereophonic sound|Stereo]]\n|runtime            = 30 minutes\n|genre              = [[Children's television series|Children's series]]<br>[[Comedy]]\n|creator            = [[Stan and Jan Berenstain]] \n|executive_producer = Stan and Jan Berenstain<br>Steven Ching<br>Scott Dyer<br>[[Michael Hirsh (producer)|Michael Hirsh]]\n|producer           = Lan Lamon<br>''Supervising producers:''<br>Patricia R. Burns<br>Jocelyn Hamilton<br>Michelle Melanson<br>Cynthia Taylor\n|voices             = [[Camilla Scott]]<br>[[Benedict Campbell|Ben Campbell]]<br>[[Michael Cera]]<br>[[Tajja Isen]]<br>[[Corinne Conley]]<br>Leslie Carlson<br>Amanda Soha<br>Marc McCulkin\n|narrated           =  \n|theme_music_composer = Stan Meissner\n|opentheme          = \"The Berenstain Bears\" by [[Lee Ann Womack]]\n|endtheme           = \"The Berenstain Bears\" (Instrumental)\n|composer          = Ray Parker<br>Tom Szczesniak\n|company            = [[Nelvana|Nelvana Limited]]<br>AGOGO Entertainment\n|country            = Canada\n|language           = English\n|network            = [[PBS Kids]] (US)<br>[[Treehouse TV]] (Canada)\n|first_aired        = {{Start date|2003|1|6}}\n|last_aired         = {{End date|2004|12|6}}\n|num_seasons        = 3\n|num_episodes       = 40\n|list_episodes      = List of The Berenstain Bears (2003 TV series) episodes\n|preceded_by        = [[The Berenstain Bears (1985 TV series)|''The Berenstain Bears'' (1985 TV series)]]\n|website            = http://www.berenstainbears.com \n}}\n\n'''''The Berenstain Bears''''' is a Canadian children's [[animated series|animated]] [[television comedy]] series based on the [[Berenstain Bears|children's book series of the same name]] by [[Stan and Jan Berenstain]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Perlmutter |first1=David |title=The Encyclopedia of American Animated Television Shows |date=2018 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-1538103739 |pages=77-78}}</ref> The series follows the lives of a family of [[anthropomorphic]] [[bear]]s who learn a [[moral]] or [[safety]]-related lesson during the course of each episode. It ran for forty episodes in three seasons.<ref>{{cite web|title=Berenstain Bears|url=http://www.nelvana.com/show/116/berenstain-bears|publisher=Corus Entertainment|accessdate=3 January 2019}}</ref> The series debuted on [[PBS Kids]] in the United States on January 6, 2003 and ended on December 6, 2004.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}} Reruns continued to air on PBS Kids until September 2, 2007.\n\n[[The Berenstain Bears (1985 TV series)|A previous ''Berenstain Bears'' cartoon]] aired in Australia and the United States from 1985 to 1987.\n\n==Synopsis==\nThe series is set in a world populated solely by anthropomorphic bears and primarily centers around the Berenstain Bears. The Berenstain Bears are a family residing in the rural community of Bear Country consisting of Mama Bear, Papa Bear, Brother Bear, and Sister Bear. Albeit numerous episodes are based on the books and promote the same morals as encouraged in the picture books from which their plots originated, the program's faithfulness to the original series is slightly mixed on account of a number of later episodes following original storylines. Nonetheless, they mostly portray the same environment depicted in the original ''Berenstain Bears'' storybooks quite accurately and concentrate on the messages and lessons learned by the family through their different experiences, such as generousity and responsibility, as well as the daily lives of the bears.\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Main|List of The Berenstain Bears (2003 TV series) episodes}}\n{{:List of The Berenstain Bears (2003 TV series) episodes}}\n\n==Cast and characters==\n\n===Main===\n*[[Michael Cera]] as Brother Bear (Episodes 1-26)\n*[[Michael D'Ascenzo]] as Brother Bear (Episodes 27-40)\n*[[Tajja Isen]] as Sister Bear\n*[[Benedict Campbell]] as Papa Q. Bear\n*[[Camilla Scott]] as Mama Bear\n\n===Recurring===\n\n====Family====\n*[[Leslie Carlson]] as Grizzly Gramps \n*[[Corinne Conley]] as Grizzly Gran\n*[[Marc McMulkin]] as Cousin Freddy\n\n====Friends====\n*Amanda Soha as Lizzy Bruin\n*Nikki Marshall as Queenie\n*[[Mark Rendall]] as Ferdy Factual\n*Gage Knox as Too-Tall\n*Patrick Salvagna as Skuzz\n*[[James Eckhouse (Canadian actor)|James Eckhouse]] as Smirk\n\n====Citizens====\n*[[Chris Wiggins]] as Squire Grizzly\n*Ellen-Ray Hennessy as Miss Grizzle\n*[[Philip Williams (actor)|Philip Williams]] as Farmer Ben\n\n==Production==\nThe show was produced by the Canadian [[animation]] company [[Nelvana]] for [[PBS Kids]]2003-present in the United States and [[Treehouse TV]] 2003-2004 in Canada. Eighty 15-minute episodes were produced, adapted from the books and also a few new stories as well, similar to the 1985 production.<ref name=gillies>{{cite news|author=Gillies, Judith S.|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2003-01-04/news/0301040264_1_stan-berenstain-berenstain-bears-bears-titles|title=Grin 'n' 'Bear' it: The Berenstains come to WTTW|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=January 4, 2003|accessdate=29 April 2018}}</ref> However, due to Canadian laws requiring Nelvana to employ only Canadian writers and artists, the Berenstains' involvement in the program was limited; They sought to exert their influence on some details, according to Stan. \"Our bears don't wear shoes, and Papa wouldn't wear his hat in the house...And we try to keep complete, total banality out of the stories.\" Common practicalities of animation did force some minor costume changes from the books, such as eliminating polka dots and plaids. (This issue also occurred in the previous animated series and specials. Only a limited amount of polka dots was allowed in the five specials.)<ref name=\"gillies\"/> The show's theme song is performed by [[Lee Ann Womack]].<ref name=gillies/> The series is supposed to supplement the 1985 series because new books were released since then, even though the two series have a radically different production style as well as a change of in-universe elements. Another issue is the two series are never seen together.\n\n===Music===\nCountry music singer-songwriter [[Lee Ann Womack]] sings the series' theme song, which was written by [[Stan Meissner]].\n\n==Broadcast==\nIt debuted in the United States on PBS Kids on January 6, 2003.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Berenstain Bears \u2013 The Nelvana-Produced Series Comes To Video For The First Time Ever|url=http://www.corusent.com/news/the-berenstain-bears-the-nelvana-produced-series-comes-to-video-for-the-first-time-ever/|publisher=Corus Entertainment Inc.|accessdate=29 April 2018|date=December 10, 2002}}</ref> Originally, it aired together with ''[[Seven Little Monsters (TV series)|Seven Little Monsters]]'' but the two shows were eventually separated.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Berenstain Bears Bring 40 Years Of Literary History To \"PBS Kids\" With Premiere Of 15-Minute Animated TV Series|url=http://www.corusent.com/news/the-berenstain-bears%c2%a8-bring-40-years-of-literary-history-to-pbs-kids-with-premiere-of-15-minute-animated-tv-series/|publisher=Corus Entertainment|date=November 14, 2002|accessdate=29 April 2018}}</ref> It also ran on [[Knowledge Network|Knowledge]] (British Columbia), [[CITV]],  [[Tiny Pop]] and [[KidsCo]] (UK), OBS (South Korea), [[YTV (TV channel)|YTV]], [[Treehouse TV]], [[Nickelodeon (Canadian TV channel)|Nickelodeon]] and [[Teletoon Retro]] in Canada. The show also broadcasts reruns on PBS Kids Sprout from the channel's inception until the network rebranded into [[Universal Kids]].\n\n==Accolades==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"\n!Year\n!Award\n!Category\n!Recipients and nominees\n!Outcome\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2004\n|[[Gemini Award]]s\n|Best Pre-School Program or Series\n|[[Stan and Jan Berenstain|Stan Berenstain, Jan Berenstain]], [[Michael Hirsh (producer)|Michael Hirsh]], Steven Ching, Scott Dyer\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|style=\"white-space:nowrap;\"|[[Young Artist Award]]s\n|style=\"white-space:nowrap;\"|Best Performance in a Voice-Over Role \u2013 Young Actress\n|[[Tajja Isen]]\n|{{nom}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*{{IMDb title|0364793|The Berenstain Bears}}\n*{{tv.com show|the-berenstain-bears|The Berenstain Bears}}\n{{Berenstain Bears}}\n{{PBS Kids shows}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Berenstain Bears (2002 TV series), The}}\n[[Category:Canadian children's animated comedy television series]]\n[[Category:2000s Canadian animated television series]]\n[[Category:2003 Canadian television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2004 Canadian television series endings]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Berenstain Bears]]\n[[Category:Canadian television programs based on children's books]]\n[[Category:Canadian preschool education television series]]\n[[Category:PBS original programming]]\n[[Category:Canadian animated television programs featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:Television series by Nelvana]]\n[[Category:PBS Kids shows]]\n[[Category:Treehouse TV shows]]\n[[Category:YTV shows]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about bears]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about children]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about families]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about siblings]]\n[[Category:Canadian television series with live action and animation]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|The Berenstain Bears (1985 TV series)}}\n{{more citations needed|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox television\n|show_name          = The Berenstain Bears\n|image              =\n|caption            =\n|camera             = \n|pictu